#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/polynomial/polynomial.py:docstring
#: of numpy.polynomial.polynomial.polyfit:110
msgid "Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/polynomial/polynomial.py:docstring
#: of numpy.polynomial.polynomial.polyfit:111
msgid ""
"The solution is the coefficients of the polynomial `p` that minimizes the "
"sum of the weighted squared errors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/polynomial/polynomial.py:docstring
#: of numpy.polynomial.polynomial.polyfit:114
msgid ""
"E = \\sum_j w_j^2 * |y_j - p(x_j)|^2,\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/polynomial/polynomial.py:docstring
#: of numpy.polynomial.polynomial.polyfit:116
msgid ""
"where the :math:`w_j` are the weights. This problem is solved by setting up "
"the (typically) over-determined matrix equation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/polynomial/polynomial.py:docstring
#: of numpy.polynomial.polynomial.polyfit:119
msgid ""
"V(x) * c = w * y,\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/polynomial/polynomial.py:docstring
#: of numpy.polynomial.polynomial.polyfit:121
msgid ""
"where `V` is the weighted pseudo Vandermonde matrix of `x`, `c` are the "
"coefficients to be solved for, `w` are the weights, and `y` are the observed "
"values.  This equation is then solved using the singular value decomposition "
"of `V`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/polynomial/polynomial.py:docstring
#: of numpy.polynomial.polynomial.polyfit:126
msgid ""
"If some of the singular values of `V` are so small that they are neglected "
"(and `full` == ``False``), a `~exceptions.RankWarning` will be raised.  This "
"means that the coefficient values may be poorly determined. Fitting to a "
"lower order polynomial will usually get rid of the warning (but may not be "
"what you want, of course; if you have independent reason(s) for choosing the "
"degree which isn't working, you may have to: a) reconsider those reasons, "
"and/or b) reconsider the quality of your data).  The `rcond` parameter can "
"also be set to a value smaller than its default, but the resulting fit may "
"be spurious and have large contributions from roundoff error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/polynomial/polynomial.py:docstring
#: of numpy.polynomial.polynomial.polyfit:137
msgid ""
"Polynomial fits using double precision tend to \"fail\" at about "
"(polynomial) degree 20. Fits using Chebyshev or Legendre series are "
"generally better conditioned, but much can still depend on the distribution "
"of the sample points and the smoothness of the data.  If the quality of the "
"fit is inadequate, splines may be a good alternative."
msgstr ""

